<br>
For some creatures, there are certain periods of time where a creature is more dangerous than at other points.  Recent experience with creatures that gate is one example, and I think this could apply to rampage, complete heal, unsnared runners, etc.  Basically, any time when a creature needs to be dead, and dead now. <br>
<br>
One variable mages have control over is spell damage during these critical times.  Most of the times it's when you hear the preverbial &quot;NUKE NOW!&quot; command.  At this point, I would typically try to apply the highest DPS I can, by clicking my spell icon as often as possible (time) for the biggest bang I can do in that time (damage). <br>
<br>
What if just before that critical juncture, we were to use Wrath of the Elements?  Since it is damage over time, we can start the spell before the creature becomes a bit more dangerous, and it will be doing it's damage during the critical phase.  This would add to our spell DPS when it's most needed, bypassing a bit of the &quot;time casting&quot; element. <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 1879<br> <font color=#333333>(9/23/02 7:17:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1552.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Wrath of Elements (mage dot) perhaps a viable raid spell</span><hr size=1> Based on another suggestion, I tried substituting rains for dots.  For efficiency and DPS, nothing beats rains, assuming they are applicable, i.e. single target, aggro well under control.  That is, the typical raid situation you described.  Also at the point, all debuffs should be on, except for the rumored <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &quot;mob is about to die so it resists everything all of a sudden.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
But in that case, it seems to me that stacking a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Sirocco</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Maelstrom of Electricity</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, both rains, likely meets your goals better than <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Wrath of Elements</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Since both are three waves, which I assume are three ticks, you would be hard pressed to fit in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  WoE</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in addition just before the danger zone.  With two rains, it would be hard to justify another spell slot for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  WoE</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> on top of whatever nuke or nukes you were using.  Plus, if you did need to squeeze out more DPS, you would have to wait more time to squeeze out another <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  WoE</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, 5 ticks, than another rain, 3 ticks.<br>
<br>
The advantage of the mage dots is that they have adequate efficiency, while being less likely to break root or get aggro.  My main use of them has been to chain them between casts of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Boots of Bladecalling</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  With a 17 second cast time, boots have a built-in, no brainer delay, which means they rarely grab aggro even when chaining.  And at only 600 points each, they are less likely to break root than our kilonukes.  But they are slow.  With KEI, I like to speed up the DPS, so the obvious thing to do is alternate real nukes and boot nukes.  When I did this however with my 800-1000 point nukes, I found I broke root and got aggro too often.  When I used the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &quot;softer&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> DoTs instead of harder nukes, I was able to largely alternate these with boots, and almost never break root or get aggro, which was my objective.<br>
<br>
However, I have recently gotten <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Spell Casting Subtelty 3</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Maelstrom of Electricity</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Now I find I can often alternate boots and rains, and this is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>much</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> faster and more efficient.<br>
<br>
The magnitude of our dots is small.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Elemental Maelstrom</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> does between 600-700 damage, depending on how DoTs are resolved server side, and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Wrath of the Elephants</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> does 800-900.  What you suggest probably makes a lot of sense for classes with longer and stronger damage over time spells, but probably does not make sense for magicians, since rains do a better job of that.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> EDIT:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  On the other hand, if the rain causes you to get summoned, that might be bad.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> WoE</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is less likely to get you summoned, and won't hurt you if are, which a rain will do if you are summoned into it.  Perhaps....<br>
