<br>
I like my DoTs.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I like them too.  The question is, when do you use them rather than a straight nuke?  I have described elsewhere how at 49th, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Elemental Maelstrom</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> was a better choice for me than <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Shock of Swords</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> pre-<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Luclin</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, so here let's compare the higher level pair of spells:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magecompendium.com/Spells/Wrath_of_The_Elements.htm">Wrath of the Elephants</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is a 55th level damage over time spell for 265 mana, with 350 initial direct damage, and 90 damage per tick for 5 ticks.  It takes 7 seconds to cast, with 2.5 second recast delay, is evocation based and saves versus magic.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magecompendium.com/Spells/Shock_of_Steel.htm">Shock of Steel</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is the closest comparable nuke.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> SoS</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is a 57th level conjuration shock for 275 mana that does 800ish damage, takes 6 seconds to cast with a 2.5 second recast delay.<br>
<br>
Assuming that for whatever reason, either bolts, rains, or fire based spells are not appropriate for the target, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> WoE</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is clearly a viable source of damage for levels 55 and 56.  However, at 57th under those circumstances, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> SoS</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> would become the default choice.<br>
<br>
Assume the mage has both the summoned focus earring and bracer, to save mana and increase damage, no AA, and we will consider both possible specializations.<br>
<br>
Depending on how damage over time spells are resolved server side against static targets <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (classes that use DOTs extensively appear to have demonstrated that there is either a 15% or 33% increase in damage per tick if the target has not moved that tick)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> WoE</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> does between 800 and 900 points of damage.  This yields 3.45 DPM in the worst case <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (moving target, conjure spec)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, or 4.25 in the best case <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (server side bonus for static target, evoke spec)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Without the server side bonus, the evoke specialist gets 3.77 DPM.<br>
<br>
In contrast, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> SoS</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> would be expected to do 875 damage with the focus bracer, for 3.64 DPM for an evoke specialist, or 3.98 DPM for a conjuration specialist.<br>
<br>
So these spells are very close in efficiency, depending on specialization, amd whether the server side bonus for static targets is applied.  At higher levels, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> SoS</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> increases to 825 base damage, or 900ish with the bracer, and with the AA skill <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Spell Casting Fury</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the gap widens further as criticals, like the focus bracer, do not apply to DOTs.<br>
<br>
However, despite all this, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> WoE</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is a reasonably efficient source of damage for evocation specialists where either bolts, fire, or rains are not appropriate.<br>
<br>
Given that the spell is adequate, when would you choose to use <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> WoE</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> over the more straight forward and generally applicable <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> SoS</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->?<br>
<br>
The advantage of shock nukes such as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> SoS</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is that they are fast, direct, efficient, and not terribly dependent on particular circumstances.  If you don't want a bolt, fire, or rains, then shocks are in general the best alternative.  These are the same circumstances that the mage DOTs are applicable.  So why wouldn't you cast <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> SoS</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> instead?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Breaking Root:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I have observed that larger nukes are more likely to break root than smaller nukes.  I can only recall seeing <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> WoE</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> break a root once or maybe twice, it has an initial DD component of 350.  Most of the time, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Boots of Bladecalling</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> do not break root at 600 points a shot, but it is not uncommon.  Waves of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Sirroco</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> at 630 can also break root often enough to pay attention.  However, I notice that I break root much more often with nukes that do 800 or more base damage, such as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> SoS</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Shock of Fiery Blades</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
If it were important to not break root, I might choose to use a DOT.  For example, there is no enchanter, but a priest is using root <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (aka &quot;ghetto mezz&quot;)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> instead.  I might want to malosini and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> WoE</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the add; I certainly would not want to nuke it.  Likewise soloing, I might conclude that I want to take less chance of breaking the earth elemental root.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Aggro Management:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Damage spells generate hate proportional to their nominal damage, that is, not including resists, focus item effects, or critical hits.  However, hate also decays over time.  A nuke 30 seconds ago is less hateful than a nuke now.  DOTs do their damage in smaller chunks out over five ticks.  So not only do they generate less hate when they hit, intially and each tick, but the hate generated fades from memory more quickly.  That is, for the same amount of damage, you generate less hate.  Better, a resisted <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> SoS</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> still generates 800 points of hate, but a resisted <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> WoE</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> generates only 350 points of hate, since the tick damage does not occur and therefore generates no hate.<br>
<br>
For nukers, there is an easy alternative, which is to wait a little while before nuking again.  This allows the hate from the previous spells to decay enough to allow the caster to nuke without taking aggro away from the current tank.  However, this is not always practical. <br>
<br>
For example, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Boots of Bladecalling</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> have a long, 17 second cast, right click 600 point nuke.  Depending on the mob and the fight, casting a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;hard&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> nuke immediately after a boot nuke may get aggro, especially soloing.  On the other hand, the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;softer&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> DOT may be castable between boot clicks without getting aggro.  I speak from direct experience here.  Another example might be chain casting pets.  Your pet is at 30% health or so, and you have the time and mana to cast something, but you don't want to risk either breaking root or getting aggro right before you chain the next pet.  So you cast the DOT instead.  Chain casting pets is a very mana efficient fighting technique, but it is slow, and a full mana bar is a sin against <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Karana</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  In this case, the nuke is not applicable.<br>
<br>
In other words, if one is very busy, and can't afford to wait for the right time to nuke, or want to avoid the chance of breaking root or taking aggro, since <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> WoE</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is an adequately efficient alternative to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> SoS</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, it might well be the best spell in that situation.<br>
<br>
However, I am not convinced that it is a viable choice for tagging runners, or building up a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;pulse&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of incoming damage in order to shorten the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;danger phase&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> at the end of the life of certain mobs.  It seems to me that <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magecompendium.com/Spells/Char.htm">Char</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is a better choice for runners, as it is faster and deals nearly as much damage, and rains are generally a better choice for bringing the end of a fight to faster conclusion.<br>
<br>
Last observation.  I have recently acquired <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Spell Casting Subtley 3</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and I have found that I can now often substitute rains for dots between boot casts.  I highly recommend this ability for those who want to continuously rain down fire from the heavens.<br>
